Lily sat on the edge of her bed, the shattered pieces of her porcelain doll scattered like fallen stars at her feet. “It’s ruined! My life is *over*!” she cried, her voice trembling as she exaggerated the loss—after all, to a seven-year-old, a broken doll felt like the end of the world. Her favorite companion, a gift from her grandmother, lay in jagged fragments, and hot tears spilled onto her cheeks.

A soft knock came at the door before her mother entered, her eyes warm with understanding. “Hey, love. Can I sit?” Lily didn’t answer, instead burying her face in her well-worn pillow. It smelled of lavender and safety, the familiar scent grounding her as her mother settled beside her on the quilt.

“It hurts, doesn’t it?” her mother murmured. “But come look with me.” They walked to the window, where the afternoon sky stretched wide and soft. Lazy clouds drifted overhead—one shaped like a drowsy bear, another like a ship sailing on blue silk. “See how they change?” her mother said, pointing. “Even when they look thick and gray, the sun’s still there behind them. Love’s like that, Lily. It doesn’t vanish when things break. It’s the quiet force that mends us, even when we forget to feel it.”

Lily watched the clouds shift, her breathing slowing. She realized she *had* been exaggerating—the doll could be glued back together, or she could create a new memory with her grandmother. But the steady pressure of her mother’s hand on her shoulder, the unspoken promise in her gaze… that was irreplaceable. That night, as she carefully placed the doll’s pieces into a keepsake box, Lily whispered into her pillow, “Thank you for loving me.” Outside, a single cloud drifted past the moon, soft and forgiving—reminding her that some things, like love, were always there, waiting to be seen. [end of text]


